-- Banco Panamericano, Grupo Bimbo, Lan, Urbi: Latin America Equity Preview
-- B y   J o n a t h a n   J .   L e v i n
-- 2010-11-10T06:36:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-10/banco-panamericano-grupo-bimbo-lan-urbi-latin-america-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  The  MSCI Latin America Index  declined 1 percent to 4,628.01,
the biggest drop since Oct. 21.  Brazil  Banco Panamericano SA  (BPNM4 BS): The lender said Grupo
Silvio Santos, its controlling shareholder, will inject 2.5
billion reais ($1.5 billion) into the bank to shore up its
capital after accounting “inconsistencies” were detected. The
shares dropped 6.8 percent to 6.77 reais, the biggest decline
since February.  BM&FBovespa SA  (BVMF3 BZ): The owner of Latin America’s
largest exchange reported third-quarter adjusted net income of
389.2 million reais, up 15 percent from the same period last
year, according to a regulatory filing. The shares declined 2.6
percent to 13.69 reais.  Banco Santander Brasil SA  (SANB11 BS): The lender approved
stock repurchases of up to 1.45 million units, representing 79.9
million common shares and 72.6 million preferred shares, or
about 0.21 percent of its total shares in circulation, according
to a regulatory filing. The shares fell 5.6 percent to 24.5
reais, the biggest drop since May.  Chile  Lan Airlines SA  (LAN CC): Latin America’s largest carrier
by market value plans to appeal an 8.2 million-euro fine handed
down by the European Union for fixing cargo fees, according to a
statement posted on the website of Chile’s securities regulator.
The shares declined 0.2 percent to 14,799 pesos.  Colombia  Banco de Bogota SA  (BOGOTA CB): Colombia’s second-biggest
lender plans to issue 2.5 trillion pesos ($1.4 billion) of
convertible debt. The shares fell 0.2 percent to 54,300 pesos.  Mexico  Grupo Bimbo SAB de CV  (BIMBOA MM): The company’s credit
rating was placed under review for a possible downgrade by
Standard & Poor’s after the Mexican breadmaker acquired Sara
Lee’s North American bakery business. The shares jumped the most
since March, advancing 4.6 percent to 101.9 pesos.  Kimberly-Clark de Mexico SAB de CV  (KIMBERA MM): The
nation’s biggest consumer products company said it sold 4
billion pesos in fixed- and floating-rate bonds in the local
market. The shares fell 1 percent to 76.83 pesos.  Urbi Desarrollos Urbanos SAB  (URBI* MM): Mexico’s third-
largest homebuilder signed an agreement with Banco Santander SA
to promote mortgages together. The shares dropped 0.2 percent to
27.1 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
